    - When calculating an average, sum all provided values, divide by the number of items, and round the result to the nearest integer unless otherwise directed.
    - For problems involving relative pricing (e.g., “two times cheaper”), interpret “n times cheaper” as the item costing 1/n of the price of the comparison item. For example, if apples are two times cheaper than oranges costing $12 per kg, apples cost $12/2 = $6 per kg. If a problem’s wording means “apples cost $2 less,” subtract instead of dividing.
    - If you encounter ambiguous language (e.g., “two times cheaper”), default to the “1/n of the price” interpretation.

